00:28.362 --> 00:30.656
[chuckles]
Time will tell.

00:30.656 --> 00:32.282
<i>- My name is Brett Onnink.</i>

00:32.282 --> 00:34.076
<i>I'm 45.</i>
<i>I'm from South Bend, Indiana.</i>

00:34.076 --> 00:36.328
And I've been smithing
and making knives

00:36.328 --> 00:37.496
<i>for about six years.</i>

00:37.496 --> 00:39.540
My wife's patient.
[laughs]

00:39.540 --> 00:41.750
And, uh, she never quite
understood all the money

00:41.750 --> 00:43.001
that I would spend
or the amount of time

00:43.001 --> 00:44.545
I would spend
doing this at night

00:44.545 --> 00:45.879
<i>when I could</i>
<i>be doing other things</i>

00:45.879 --> 00:48.799
like, um,
spending time with her.

00:48.799 --> 00:52.052
<i>- My name's Chuck Fowler,</i>
<i>I'm from Interlachen, Florida.</i>

00:52.052 --> 00:56.682
I'm 47 or 48 years old.
I can't remember.

00:56.682 --> 00:58.433
<i>Grew up</i>
<i>in a bladesmithing shop.</i>

00:58.433 --> 01:01.019
My father's been a bladesmith
since I was a kid.

01:01.019 --> 01:02.437
<i>I really want</i>
<i>to do this competition</i>

01:02.437 --> 01:04.106
<i>to see if I can</i>
<i>actually compete.</i>

01:04.106 --> 01:07.025
And my wife and kids
wanted me to do it.

01:07.025 --> 01:09.611
<i>- My name's Cole Coffer.</i>
<i>I'm 27 years old.</i>

01:09.611 --> 01:12.281
I forge blades
and ironwork full-time

01:12.281 --> 01:14.533
out of my shop
in Dawsonville, Georgia.

01:14.533 --> 01:16.285
<i>Dawsonville</i>
<i>is a pretty small town.</i>

01:16.285 --> 01:20.163
Our city hall is now
half NASCAR museum,

01:20.163 --> 01:22.291
half moonshine distillery.

01:22.291 --> 01:24.167
<i>And you can go</i>
<i>and buy moonshine</i>

01:24.167 --> 01:26.420
and do whatever you do
at city hall.

01:26.420 --> 01:28.589
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:28.589 --> 01:30.716
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:30.716 --> 01:33.176
Each of you is here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:33.176 --> 01:35.012
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:35.012 --> 01:37.639
specifically designed
to push you to your limits,

01:37.639 --> 01:39.516
all in front of
a panel of expert judges.

01:39.516 --> 01:41.101
These are the men who decide
which of you

01:41.101 --> 01:42.978
will be our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:42.978 --> 01:45.063
and take home
that check for $10,000.

01:45.063 --> 01:47.899
Up first,
ABS master smith J. Nielson.

01:47.899 --> 01:50.277
Next, historic weapons
re-creation specialist

01:50.277 --> 01:52.112
David Baker.

01:52.112 --> 01:56.408
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:56.408 --> 01:58.577
Here at The Forge,
we're all about what it takes

01:58.577 --> 01:59.870
to make a knife,
and then I thought,

01:59.870 --> 02:01.747
"What does it really take
to become

02:01.747 --> 02:03.457
a 'Forged in Fire' champion?"

02:03.457 --> 02:05.500
And I think we've come up
with the right answer.

02:05.500 --> 02:08.628
On your anvils is a cloth.
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:08.628 --> 02:10.464
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

02:10.464 --> 02:11.465
- [laughs]

02:11.465 --> 02:12.716
Fantastic.

02:12.716 --> 02:14.134
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:14.134 --> 02:16.720
- Big nuts, gentlemen.

02:16.720 --> 02:19.681
Those are
industrial-sized nuts,

02:19.681 --> 02:22.768
1045 medium carbon steel,
and along with that,

02:22.768 --> 02:25.771
you have a piece of W1
high carbon steel bar stock.

02:25.771 --> 02:28.315
You'll have to combine
those two steels together

02:28.315 --> 02:30.484
to forge your blade
into your signature style.

02:30.484 --> 02:33.236
<i>- I look down on my anvil,</i>
<i>and I see a giant nut</i>

02:33.236 --> 02:35.280
<i>and a piece of bar stock.</i>

02:35.280 --> 02:38.617
I'm just thinking of all the
crazy ways things can go wrong.

02:38.617 --> 02:40.952
<i>You got to forge weld</i>
<i>those two pieces together.</i>

02:40.952 --> 02:43.830
<i>One doesn't have a lot</i>
<i>of high carbon content to it.</i>

02:43.830 --> 02:45.874
<i>This is gonna be</i>
<i>a challenge.</i>

02:45.874 --> 02:47.626
- Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:47.626 --> 02:49.127
you'll be attaching
handles to those blades

02:49.127 --> 02:51.004
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

02:51.004 --> 02:53.090
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:53.090 --> 02:55.676
in a "Forged in Fire" first...

02:55.676 --> 02:57.552
dual strength test:

02:57.552 --> 02:58.887
a sheet metal stab...

02:58.887 --> 03:00.847
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:00.847 --> 03:03.183
And a baton nut chop.

03:03.183 --> 03:05.394
Then your blades will be
tested for edge retention

03:05.394 --> 03:07.938
in a water bottle slice.

03:07.938 --> 03:09.773
Gentlemen, you will have
three hours in which

03:09.773 --> 03:11.441
to forge those blades.

03:11.441 --> 03:13.902
Your three hours starts now.

03:13.902 --> 03:17.948
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:17.948 --> 03:21.576
The W1 steel
is a higher carbon content.

03:21.576 --> 03:24.037
How much higher carbon
are we talking about?

03:24.037 --> 03:26.623
- The W1 is closer to, like,
a 1084.

03:26.623 --> 03:28.834
- Okay.
- It's a higher carbon content.

03:28.834 --> 03:32.212
The 1045 on the nuts
is hardenable,

03:32.212 --> 03:34.714
but if these guys are really
blasting the heat into that,

03:34.714 --> 03:36.716
you could start
burning carbon out.

03:36.716 --> 03:39.219
- That would make
for some weaker steel.

03:39.219 --> 03:42.097
- And what do I do
with this giant nut?

03:42.097 --> 03:43.723
I thought, "Well,
it doesn't have to be

03:43.723 --> 03:45.809
the whole piece incorporated."

03:45.809 --> 03:48.145
My game plan is to
stretch the bar stock out

03:48.145 --> 03:50.730
to a flat square stock
that I can actually use.

03:50.730 --> 03:52.649
Take the nut,
cut a piece of it off,

03:52.649 --> 03:54.317
get it in the usable
bar stocks,

03:54.317 --> 03:56.653
forge weld them together,
get 'er done.

03:56.653 --> 03:58.447
<i>I'm gonna forge weld</i>
<i>the nut pieces</i>

03:58.447 --> 04:00.574
<i>to the blade as bolsters.</i>

04:00.574 --> 04:03.326
<i>Bolsters are the transition</i>
<i>from the ricasso</i>

04:03.326 --> 04:05.579
to the actual handle itself.

04:05.579 --> 04:06.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:06.955 --> 04:08.707
- Chuck's an
industrial welder,

04:08.707 --> 04:11.334
so to cut the nut,
he went straight to the torch.

04:11.334 --> 04:13.253
<i>- The acetylene torch,</i>
<i>you can cut any</i>

04:13.253 --> 04:15.297
<i>high carbon, low carbon steel.</i>

04:15.297 --> 04:17.257
<i>Plus, it's</i>
<i>way more fun to use.</i>

04:17.257 --> 04:19.092
You know, sparks,
[bleep] flying--oops.

04:19.092 --> 04:21.470
[bleep] flying everywhere.

04:21.470 --> 04:23.388
- Cole's looking
a little lost here.

04:23.388 --> 04:25.891
- I think that Cole might be
waiting on the torch there.

04:25.891 --> 04:27.851
- I'll just take
that torch from you.

04:27.851 --> 04:29.895
- You got it.
- Appreciate it, man.

04:29.895 --> 04:32.272
Torch is the fastest way to go,

04:32.272 --> 04:35.692
and I cut a piece
of mild steel from the nut.

04:35.692 --> 04:38.111
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:38.111 --> 04:41.656
For my plan,
I immediately think of San Mai

04:41.656 --> 04:46.036
<i>or taco, just combining</i>
<i>the two together.</i>

04:46.036 --> 04:48.121
<i>I don't want the nut steel</i>

04:48.121 --> 04:50.665
<i>anywhere near</i>
<i>the cutting edge of my blade.</i>

04:50.665 --> 04:52.584
- I don't think that Brett
likes the progress

04:52.584 --> 04:54.294
the chop saw is making.

04:54.294 --> 04:56.087
- Nuts.
- It ain't cutting.

04:56.087 --> 04:57.380
- Nope.

04:57.380 --> 04:58.507
- The chop saw does not have

04:58.507 --> 05:00.091
enough guts to cut that thing.

05:00.091 --> 05:02.177
<i>So I have to cut it</i>
<i>with the torch.</i>

05:02.177 --> 05:04.429
<i>I've never cut up</i>
<i>a nut like that.</i>

05:04.429 --> 05:06.640
Toughest part about this nut
is trying to figure out

05:06.640 --> 05:07.724
how to crack it.

05:07.724 --> 05:09.100
[laughs]

05:09.100 --> 05:11.853
I love dad jokes.

05:11.853 --> 05:13.772
<i>This nut is such an odd shape.</i>

05:13.772 --> 05:15.232
<i>It's a challenge</i>
<i>to try and figure out</i>

05:15.232 --> 05:17.108
<i>how to process the material.</i>

05:17.108 --> 05:19.194
I need to make it a San Mai,
because that's all I know

05:19.194 --> 05:21.154
how to do with what I have.

05:21.154 --> 05:24.491
<i>And I hope like crazy</i>
<i>I can pull it off.</i>

05:24.491 --> 05:26.827
<i>- Well, I'm not keen</i>
<i>on the torch.</i>

05:26.827 --> 05:28.411
<i>But it looks like</i>
<i>that's the only way</i>

05:28.411 --> 05:30.247
<i>I'm gonna have to go</i>
<i>with this.</i>

05:30.247 --> 05:33.708
My game plan is slab off
a piece of the nut,

05:33.708 --> 05:37.087
<i>forge it flat,</i>
<i>forge the W1 flat,</i>

05:37.087 --> 05:39.673
<i>make the nut into two pieces,</i>

05:39.673 --> 05:41.550
<i>San Mai my W1,</i>

05:41.550 --> 05:42.884
<i>and make a blade from that.</i>

05:42.884 --> 05:44.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:44.803 --> 05:47.556
- I think it's gonna be
hard to keep the mild steel

05:47.556 --> 05:50.141
separated from
the hardenable steel.

05:50.141 --> 05:52.185
- How many of these smiths
are just gonna go with

05:52.185 --> 05:54.062
their hardenable steel
but they draw it out

05:54.062 --> 05:57.274
and take their mild steel and
make it as part of the tang?

05:57.274 --> 05:59.401
- You know, you don't really
want that junction point

05:59.401 --> 06:01.736
right in your tang,
especially when I'm intending

06:01.736 --> 06:04.030
to beat the living hell
out of these knives too.

06:04.030 --> 06:05.740
<i>- Feeling pretty comfortable</i>
<i>right now.</i>

06:05.740 --> 06:07.617
Well, I got
my high carbon steel billet

06:07.617 --> 06:09.077
<i>to where it needs to be.</i>

06:09.077 --> 06:10.871
Now it's time
to take the mild steel

06:10.871 --> 06:12.706
<i>and circumference</i>
<i>the blade on each side.</i>

06:12.706 --> 06:15.667
- Chuck has used
the mild steel to create

06:15.667 --> 06:17.627
an integral guard
or bolster.

06:17.627 --> 06:19.421
- That's a good way
to use the materials.

06:19.421 --> 06:21.590
- One takes a little more heat
than the other.

06:21.590 --> 06:24.134
So you're running the risk
of burning the other one.

06:24.134 --> 06:26.595
But you have to have
part of the mild steel

06:26.595 --> 06:28.179
onto the high carbon.

06:28.179 --> 06:29.598
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

06:29.598 --> 06:31.850
- I want to have
a pretty beefy blade

06:31.850 --> 06:34.227
for the
double strength testing,

06:34.227 --> 06:36.062
<i>'cause that's gonna be</i>
<i>a pretty gnarly test.</i>

06:36.062 --> 06:39.232
<i>So I'm gonna make</i>
<i>a drop point</i>

06:39.232 --> 06:41.401
<i>recurve camp knife.</i>

06:41.401 --> 06:44.571
- Cole's working a tip into his
blade over there right now.

06:44.571 --> 06:46.656
Interesting.

06:46.656 --> 06:48.325
There's no forge welding
happening yet.

06:48.325 --> 06:49.993
- Not yet.

06:49.993 --> 06:51.411
- You guys want to take
a closer look?

06:51.411 --> 06:52.704
- You bet.

06:52.704 --> 06:55.457
<i>[classical music]</i>

06:55.457 --> 06:56.916
- Cole.

06:56.916 --> 07:00.378
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:00.378 --> 07:02.464
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:02.464 --> 07:05.800
- The reason I want to put
this point on my knife first

07:05.800 --> 07:09.262
is so that I know where
to put that mild steel.

07:09.262 --> 07:12.140
<i>I don't want it anywhere near</i>
<i>the tip or the cutting edge.</i>

07:12.140 --> 07:15.060
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:15.060 --> 07:17.812
[bleep].
- Oh!

07:17.812 --> 07:19.105
- [bleep].

07:19.105 --> 07:20.857
<i>I just smashed</i>

07:20.857 --> 07:22.609
<i>the whole back end</i>
<i>of my knife.</i>

07:22.609 --> 07:26.112
I know that this little thin
area that I just created

07:26.112 --> 07:27.947
is gonna be a weak spot
on my blade.

07:27.947 --> 07:30.575
<i>And right now,</i>
<i>for the first time,</i>

07:30.575 --> 07:32.577
I'm feeling the clock
counting down.

07:32.577 --> 07:35.413
- Bladesmiths,
half your time in this

07:35.413 --> 07:37.415
first round of competition
has elapsed.

07:37.415 --> 07:41.044
<i>- Now I've got</i>
<i>to figure out a plan B,</i>

07:41.044 --> 07:43.046
and I'm not really sure what
I'm gonna do right now.

07:43.046 --> 07:46.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.883 --> 07:49.552
<i>- My San Mai billet is ugly.</i>

07:49.552 --> 07:51.554
<i>The pieces are not</i>
<i>very uniform.</i>

07:51.554 --> 07:53.973
There is 1/8 inch gaps
between them.

07:53.973 --> 07:57.268
<i>And for a forge welding</i>
<i>process, that's really bad.</i>

07:57.268 --> 07:59.104
- I'm wondering
what's going on with Brett.

07:59.104 --> 08:01.731
He's got three full layers,
but they're not even.

08:01.731 --> 08:03.274
They're not cleaned.

08:03.274 --> 08:05.360
He's spending
a lot of time fluxing,

08:05.360 --> 08:06.986
and I can see seams in there.

08:06.986 --> 08:08.196
So I'm really worried he's
gonna have a lot

08:08.196 --> 08:10.031
of inclusions in that weld.

08:10.031 --> 08:12.575
- Flux is just, like, a sweet
little magical pixie dust

08:12.575 --> 08:14.119
<i>that you put on your steel</i>

08:14.119 --> 08:15.870
<i>that drops</i>
<i>the surface temperature,</i>

08:15.870 --> 08:17.872
<i>making it a little bit</i>
<i>more liquid.</i>

08:17.872 --> 08:19.791
<i>That will help start</i>
<i>closing those gaps up</i>

08:19.791 --> 08:22.252
when I start
forging it together.

08:22.252 --> 08:24.671
These dials do anything,
or am I just, like--

08:24.671 --> 08:27.298
My forge isn't hot enough,
and I keep adjusting it,

08:27.298 --> 08:29.217
but it doesn't seem
to be getting any hotter.

08:29.217 --> 08:31.344
- Right tightens it,
closes it.

08:36.349 --> 08:38.435
[laughs]

08:38.435 --> 08:42.439
Crisis averted.
Thanks, Bill.

08:42.439 --> 08:45.108
- I got the W1 forged
to the thickness I want it.

08:45.108 --> 08:47.694
<i>I got my nut pieces welded.</i>

08:47.694 --> 08:49.404
<i>I feel like</i>
<i>I'm getting behind,</i>

08:49.404 --> 08:51.823
<i>but I'm trying to work</i>
<i>as smart as I can.</i>

08:51.823 --> 08:55.368
- Look at Bill go.
Nice and steady and smooth.

08:55.368 --> 08:57.912
- His pace is just kind of
a little slower.

08:57.912 --> 09:00.415
- He only moves
as fast as he has to.

09:00.415 --> 09:02.459
- If you have
a methodical approach,

09:02.459 --> 09:04.669
<i>you'll find out your work</i>
<i>will be better in the end,</i>

09:04.669 --> 09:06.755
where you won't have
to be correcting mistakes

09:06.755 --> 09:10.091
that you made by going--
doing something too fast.

09:10.091 --> 09:12.135
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

09:12.135 --> 09:14.596
<i>- Now that I got</i>
<i>the bolsters forge welded,</i>

09:14.596 --> 09:16.514
I'll start forging
the blade out.

09:16.514 --> 09:18.892
<i>What I'm planning to make</i>
<i>is a tanto-style knife.</i>

09:18.892 --> 09:21.019
<i>It's a pretty thick spine.</i>

09:21.019 --> 09:23.521
It should take
the batoning pretty good.

09:23.521 --> 09:26.524
- Well, Chuck has really
been able to slow things down

09:26.524 --> 09:28.651
and be very deliberate
about what he's doing.

09:28.651 --> 09:30.945
That's probably a pace
that comes with

09:30.945 --> 09:32.822
relaxed confidence.
- Yeah.

09:32.822 --> 09:34.783
- A lot of people
come up to me and think

09:34.783 --> 09:36.993
I'm an angry person
just by the way I look.

09:36.993 --> 09:39.746
<i>But I'm actually not.</i>
<i>I'm actually a nice guy.</i>

09:39.746 --> 09:42.749
It's just the look I have.
I mean, I can't help it, folks.

09:42.749 --> 09:45.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:45.502 --> 09:48.254
- That is a very, very
skinny bar of steel

09:48.254 --> 09:49.923
that Cole has there.

09:49.923 --> 09:51.883
- Every time he forges it down,

09:51.883 --> 09:53.968
he's smashing it flatter
and flatter and flatter.

09:53.968 --> 09:56.012
The spine has now gotten
so thin

09:56.012 --> 09:57.806
that I'd just flip it over
and make that side the edge.

09:57.806 --> 09:58.932
- Yeah, exactly.

09:58.932 --> 10:00.308
- Throw it away.
- Yeah.

10:00.308 --> 10:02.185
- Get a new piece.
- Start over.

10:02.185 --> 10:04.479
- I'm trying to get
the forge weld to stick,

10:04.479 --> 10:07.398
and I affected
the structure of my blade.

10:07.398 --> 10:09.359
<i>My blade's so weak</i>
<i>at that spot,</i>

10:09.359 --> 10:12.487
<i>so I'm gonna move on</i>
<i>to another process.</i>

10:12.487 --> 10:13.780
- Steel on the floor.

10:13.780 --> 10:15.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:15.240 --> 10:18.118
- My plan B is something that

10:18.118 --> 10:20.870
I would never,
ever do to a blade.

10:20.870 --> 10:23.289
But I've put myself
in this predicament

10:23.289 --> 10:25.792
<i>that I have to do this</i>
<i>to get me at least</i>

10:25.792 --> 10:27.836
<i>in the parameters</i>
<i>and have some mild steel</i>

10:27.836 --> 10:30.380
<i>integrated into</i>
<i>my high carbon steel,</i>

10:30.380 --> 10:33.299
and I'm nervous of what
the judges are gonna say.

10:33.299 --> 10:35.385
- What is this guy doing now?
What is this guy doing now?

10:35.385 --> 10:36.803
- I don't know.
He's got a backup plan.

10:36.803 --> 10:38.721
I don't know what that is.

10:38.721 --> 10:43.143
- I'm going to take the
remaining bit of my nut steel

10:43.143 --> 10:45.436
and I'm actually going to use

10:45.436 --> 10:48.148
<i>a little piece</i>
<i>that's gonna be a rivet.</i>

10:48.148 --> 10:50.358
<i>That'll go through a hole</i>
<i>that I'm gonna put</i>

10:50.358 --> 10:52.694
<i>in the ricasso of the blade.</i>

10:52.694 --> 10:54.571
- Oh, don't do it!

10:54.571 --> 10:56.865
- That hole's only gonna make
a weak blade weaker.

10:56.865 --> 10:58.783
- That's called having
a lot of faith in your blade.

10:58.783 --> 11:03.705
- Drilling a hole in a knife
is not a wise decision,

11:03.705 --> 11:06.958
because it can
make a spot that that's

11:06.958 --> 11:11.337
<i>where the blade could crack,</i>
<i>and it's already so thin.</i>

11:11.337 --> 11:15.175
The clock is ticking.
This is my last resort.

11:15.175 --> 11:16.259
[bleep].

11:16.259 --> 11:17.511
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:19.429 --> 11:24.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:24.726 --> 11:28.062
That didn't break the knife,
but now I'm hoping

11:28.062 --> 11:30.273
that this rivet
is gonna work.

11:30.273 --> 11:33.193
If this rivet pops out,
I don't meet the parameters.

11:33.193 --> 11:35.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.403 --> 11:37.447
Awesome.

11:37.447 --> 11:39.699
<i>I know that I have at least</i>
<i>got some mild steel</i>

11:39.699 --> 11:42.911
integrated into
my high carbon steel.

11:42.911 --> 11:45.622
<i>Now I can work on my blade.</i>

11:45.622 --> 11:48.458
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:48.458 --> 11:53.004
- Bill's working smart, but
he's working at an odd pace.

11:53.004 --> 11:56.341
He'll stop. He'll look around.
He'll move across the shop.

11:56.341 --> 11:59.260
So I'm worried about his time
management for this challenge.

11:59.260 --> 12:01.262
<i>- Blades take me</i>
<i>a little time.</i>

12:01.262 --> 12:03.181
But that clock is running.

12:03.181 --> 12:05.391
<i>I had a high school teacher,</i>
<i>had a sign</i>

12:05.391 --> 12:07.852
under the clock on the wall,
says:

12:07.852 --> 12:11.022
"Time is passing.
Are you?"

12:11.022 --> 12:12.482
- Brett had
a little bit of trouble.

12:12.482 --> 12:13.983
He's constantly fluxing,
but it looks like

12:13.983 --> 12:15.318
he's got a good blade shape.

12:15.318 --> 12:17.612
Things are coming together
well for him.

12:17.612 --> 12:19.364
<i>- I'm feeling really good,</i>

12:19.364 --> 12:20.865
<i>'cause this knife</i>
<i>has turned out great.</i>

12:20.865 --> 12:21.783
<i>This blade,</i>
<i>it's gonna be simple.</i>

12:21.783 --> 12:23.201
It's gonna be robust.

12:23.201 --> 12:24.244
It's gonna be
the small-block Chevy

12:24.244 --> 12:25.912
of the knife-making world.

12:25.912 --> 12:28.373
- You only have 30 minutes
left in this round.

12:28.373 --> 12:30.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:30.833 --> 12:32.627
- Chuck just quenched.
- Yep.

12:32.627 --> 12:34.796
- Feeling pretty confident
about it.

12:34.796 --> 12:36.923
<i>It's all straight, looks good.</i>

12:36.923 --> 12:39.092
- Chuck has turned
his forge off.

12:39.092 --> 12:40.635
- He didn't check for hardness,

12:40.635 --> 12:43.596
so he just believes
that his blade is hard

12:43.596 --> 12:45.390
and good to go at this point.

12:45.390 --> 12:48.977
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:48.977 --> 12:51.062
- It's grabbing right there.

12:51.062 --> 12:54.107
Negative.
The tip is still soft.

12:54.107 --> 12:56.859
<i>I think I didn't get the tip</i>
<i>quite hot enough.</i>

12:56.859 --> 12:59.487
I got to go right back in
for another quench.

12:59.487 --> 13:01.030
- Remember, kids,
check your blade's hardness

13:01.030 --> 13:03.283
before you turn your forge off.

13:03.283 --> 13:05.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:05.785 --> 13:08.454
- Bill's blade, mighty hot.
And it's in the quench.

13:08.454 --> 13:10.581
<i>- This is all</i>
<i>what it's about right here.</i>

13:10.581 --> 13:13.042
You're giving the blade
a new life,

13:13.042 --> 13:16.045
<i>and it looks good,</i>
<i>looks real good.</i>

13:16.045 --> 13:17.755
Whew.

13:17.755 --> 13:20.675
- Bill's on fire.
- Bill, you're on fire!

13:20.675 --> 13:22.343
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:22.343 --> 13:24.304
- It's not really a good thing
to hear somebody

13:24.304 --> 13:26.597
shout "fire" anytime,

13:26.597 --> 13:30.310
but at home, I've set myself
on fire a few times.

13:30.310 --> 13:32.645
So I can handle that.

13:32.645 --> 13:34.731
It's not like my pants.

13:34.731 --> 13:36.607
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:36.607 --> 13:39.819
- All this work for
the past almost three hours

13:39.819 --> 13:44.365
has come down to the quench,
and I am nervous.

13:44.365 --> 13:45.867
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:45.867 --> 13:47.618
- Oh, Cole quenched.

13:47.618 --> 13:52.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:52.290 --> 13:54.417
- Cole's blade
sounds good and hard.

13:54.417 --> 13:58.087
<i>- My file's skating good,</i>
<i>so I know my blade is hard.</i>

13:58.087 --> 14:00.548
I feel great.
I've got 25 minutes left

14:00.548 --> 14:01.883
to get my knife looking good.

14:01.883 --> 14:04.469
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:04.469 --> 14:07.430
- Time is just ticking away,
and it's terrible.

14:07.430 --> 14:09.223
<i>I've got everything done</i>
<i>except for</i>

14:09.223 --> 14:10.850
the hardening part of my blade.

14:10.850 --> 14:12.435
<i>I'm gonna do</i>
<i>a differential heat treat</i>

14:12.435 --> 14:15.271
<i>and try and find steel</i>
<i>to put alongside</i>

14:15.271 --> 14:17.190
<i>my blade on either side.</i>

14:17.190 --> 14:19.275
<i>And the only thing I can find</i>
<i>is gas pipe,</i>

14:19.275 --> 14:21.110
<i>and I smash it in big blue.</i>

14:21.110 --> 14:23.446
- This is how Brett's
gonna keep that spine soft.

14:23.446 --> 14:25.948
<i>- Having a flexible spine</i>
<i>is going to help my knife</i>

14:25.948 --> 14:29.285
not shatter when they baton it
into another steel nut.

14:29.285 --> 14:31.079
- He's gonna take
the two pieces of steel

14:31.079 --> 14:32.747
that he's flattened out,
clamp them to the spine

14:32.747 --> 14:35.416
of the blade, heat that,
quench it together,

14:35.416 --> 14:37.418
then let those two pieces go.

14:37.418 --> 14:40.046
- Scrap steel on either side
acts like a heat sink.

14:40.046 --> 14:42.006
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:42.006 --> 14:44.592
So that heat doesn't get past
that steel, like, at all.

14:44.592 --> 14:47.136
<i>It's all right there</i>
<i>on the cutting edge.</i>

14:47.136 --> 14:48.763
- This is all or nothing
for Brett.

14:48.763 --> 14:51.349
He is not gonna have time
to redo this.

14:51.349 --> 14:53.392
Brett's gonna be
a hero or a goat

14:53.392 --> 14:56.145
with this maneuver
right here.

14:56.145 --> 14:57.980
- [bleats]

14:57.980 --> 15:00.191
The problem is, instead
of heating both sides

15:00.191 --> 15:02.235
and moving it back and forth
to keep everything easy,

15:02.235 --> 15:03.820
Brett's going very slow,

15:03.820 --> 15:05.696
so he's blasting the heat
on the tip,

15:05.696 --> 15:07.281
and then by the time that
he gets to the choil area,

15:07.281 --> 15:08.825
the tip's cold again.

15:08.825 --> 15:11.327
- Oh, Brett,
you're killing me, man.

15:11.327 --> 15:12.829
<i>- Time is just ticking away.</i>

15:12.829 --> 15:14.956
- Five minutes, bladesmiths!

15:14.956 --> 15:17.125
- I need to get this thing in
the quench as soon as possible.

15:17.125 --> 15:22.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:22.505 --> 15:24.507
- If that blade's not hard,
he's in trouble.

15:24.507 --> 15:26.175
- Well, that doesn't
sound hard.

15:26.175 --> 15:27.760
- One minute!

15:27.760 --> 15:29.387
- Not gonna happen
with one minute left.

15:29.387 --> 15:31.389
- Can't do it, no time.
- Never get it hot.

15:31.389 --> 15:33.516
- Oh, boy.
- Don't do it!

15:33.516 --> 15:35.059
You can't get it hot
in one minute.

15:35.059 --> 15:36.602
- I've got to try something.

15:36.602 --> 15:38.729
Something's
better than nothing.

15:38.729 --> 15:40.690
all: Oh!

15:40.690 --> 15:43.025
- He just--
- 30 seconds, bladesmiths.

15:43.025 --> 15:45.069
30 seconds remaining
in the round.

15:45.069 --> 15:46.362
- There's no way
he's gonna get that blade

15:46.362 --> 15:48.156
hot enough in 30 seconds.

15:48.156 --> 15:49.657
- He's gonna end up
with an even softer blade

15:49.657 --> 15:51.325
than he had before.

15:51.325 --> 15:53.161
- He just undid it.
- 10,

15:53.161 --> 15:55.830
9, 8, 7...
- Quench the blade!

15:55.830 --> 16:01.294
- 6, 5, 4, 3, 2,

16:01.294 --> 16:02.712
1.
- Oh, God.

16:02.712 --> 16:04.046
- Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

16:04.046 --> 16:05.506
Drop your tools.

16:05.506 --> 16:07.258
Pull your blade
out of the quench.

16:07.258 --> 16:09.385
This round is over.

16:09.385 --> 16:10.887
- Not even the tip
was hot enough.

16:10.887 --> 16:12.346
- He just lost
all the hardness.

16:12.346 --> 16:13.514
- Whatever hardness he had
is gone.

16:13.514 --> 16:14.891
- No, wait, just the tip.

16:14.891 --> 16:16.350
- Wow.

16:16.350 --> 16:17.894
<i>- Well, I swung</i>
<i>for the fences,</i>

16:17.894 --> 16:22.023
and I envision J. Neilson
looking down at my knife

16:22.023 --> 16:24.609
<i>disapprovingly, because he</i>
<i>really leans into that thing,</i>

16:24.609 --> 16:28.696
and he's just gonna
kill it with a file.

16:28.696 --> 16:30.573
- All right, bladesmiths,
that was a tough challenge.

16:30.573 --> 16:31.908
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

16:31.908 --> 16:33.242
at your work.

16:33.242 --> 16:34.827
Bill, you're up first.

16:34.827 --> 16:37.163
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:37.163 --> 16:39.165
<i>- I like what you got</i>
<i>going on here, Bill.</i>

16:39.165 --> 16:41.834
You got a really good shape.
Your dimensions are nice.

16:41.834 --> 16:43.753
There's a lot more grinding
to be done on this.

16:43.753 --> 16:46.088
Your tang is a little bit off
from your spine,

16:46.088 --> 16:47.715
but that's an easy fix.
- Yeah.

16:47.715 --> 16:49.675
- Bill, this design works well

16:49.675 --> 16:51.302
for the tests
that we have in hand.

16:51.302 --> 16:53.346
It looks like it's gonna
thrust with the point.

16:53.346 --> 16:55.973
It's got the width to cut
through the bottles also.

16:55.973 --> 16:57.808
Good job, sir.
- Thank you.

16:57.808 --> 17:00.144
- Chuck, please present
your blade to the judges.

17:00.144 --> 17:02.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:02.271 --> 17:04.273
<i>- Yeah, I like the overall</i>
<i>shape of the blade.</i>

17:04.273 --> 17:07.151
I'm just worried about
how thick it is on that spine.

17:07.151 --> 17:08.945
Once you get to slicing
those bottles,

17:08.945 --> 17:10.821
they don't like fat blades.

17:10.821 --> 17:12.615
So there's a lot of refinement
to do with your blade,

17:12.615 --> 17:14.325
but it's a good shape.

17:14.325 --> 17:16.577
It's just a matter of,
can you get that profile

17:16.577 --> 17:19.205
to be both a good stabber
and a good slicer?

17:19.205 --> 17:21.666
- Yes, sir.
- You're up next, Cole.

17:21.666 --> 17:23.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:23.751 --> 17:26.879
- My real concern with the
blade is having this fat tip.

17:26.879 --> 17:28.673
That's gonna be
a lot of mass

17:28.673 --> 17:31.092
to push through
in a stabbing test.

17:31.092 --> 17:34.387
My big concern is this
skinny little tang.

17:34.387 --> 17:35.930
I'm not delicate
with these things.

17:35.930 --> 17:37.682
- Yeah.
- Especially since we're doing

17:37.682 --> 17:40.059
batoning on the spine

17:40.059 --> 17:42.436
and hammering the tip
through steel.

17:42.436 --> 17:44.021
So you want as much
strength and foundation

17:44.021 --> 17:46.482
back here as you can get.

17:46.482 --> 17:48.985
- Brett, please present
your work to the judges.

17:48.985 --> 17:52.029
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:52.029 --> 17:55.700
- My big concern
is that you weren't happy

17:55.700 --> 17:57.535
with your heat treat.
- No, I was not.

17:57.535 --> 17:59.537
- And then
with 30 seconds left,

17:59.537 --> 18:03.165
what hardness was probably
in this blade is gone.

18:03.165 --> 18:05.585
So it's not properly hardened.

18:05.585 --> 18:08.671
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

18:08.671 --> 18:11.465
It's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

18:11.465 --> 18:13.217
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge is...

18:13.217 --> 18:14.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:14.677 --> 18:16.137
Brett.

18:16.137 --> 18:18.014
Your blade did not
make the cut.

18:18.014 --> 18:20.641
- Yeah, Brett, you worked
to the very last second,

18:20.641 --> 18:22.643
but there's not
a hard spot on that blade.

18:22.643 --> 18:24.270
So that's why we're gonna
let you go.

18:24.270 --> 18:25.896
- Brett,
please surrender your blade.

18:25.896 --> 18:27.523
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:27.523 --> 18:29.275
<i>- I absolutely agree</i>
<i>with the judges.</i>

18:29.275 --> 18:31.360
<i>There's no way</i>
<i>that that blade was hard,</i>

18:31.360 --> 18:32.903
and I knew that going in.

18:32.903 --> 18:34.739
<i>I don't really</i>
<i>see it as a loss.</i>

18:34.739 --> 18:36.532
<i>It's either I'm gonna win,</i>
<i>or I'm gonna learn,</i>

18:36.532 --> 18:38.409
and I'm just gonna move on
and do better for next time.

18:38.409 --> 18:41.370
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:41.370 --> 18:43.205
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.

18:43.205 --> 18:45.207
You've made it to the second
round of this competition.

18:45.207 --> 18:46.959
And now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:46.959 --> 18:48.836
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

18:48.836 --> 18:50.421
by attaching handles to them.

18:50.421 --> 18:52.715
Now, bet you're wondering
what this is right here.

18:52.715 --> 18:54.634
Right?
- Mm.

18:54.634 --> 18:57.511
- We've added a little
complication in this round.

18:57.511 --> 19:01.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:01.557 --> 19:03.392
- Mm.

19:03.392 --> 19:05.269
<i>- Bladesmiths, these are</i>
<i>foundries from which</i>

19:05.269 --> 19:07.855
<i>you will cast</i>
<i>bronze-threaded pommels</i>

19:07.855 --> 19:09.982
<i>to finish off your blade.</i>

19:09.982 --> 19:12.109
<i>- That alone's</i>
<i>over an hour by itself.</i>

19:12.109 --> 19:13.569
Not to mention
all the finish work

19:13.569 --> 19:15.363
<i>on the knife and the handle.</i>

19:15.363 --> 19:17.990
<i>I mean, it's strictly</i>
<i>gonna be under the gun.</i>

19:17.990 --> 19:19.450
- You will have
three hours in this round.

19:19.450 --> 19:20.951
Now, you can use
some of that time

19:20.951 --> 19:22.453
to address flaws or issues

19:22.453 --> 19:23.746
that were identified
in your blades.

19:23.746 --> 19:26.040
However, use your time wisely,

19:26.040 --> 19:28.292
'cause when the time runs out,
your blades will be tested

19:28.292 --> 19:31.253
for strength and durability
in a dual strength test--

19:31.253 --> 19:36.133
a baton nut chop
and a sheet metal stab--

19:36.133 --> 19:40.346
and for edge retention
in a water bottle slice.

19:40.346 --> 19:42.932
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts...

19:42.932 --> 19:44.016
now.

19:44.016 --> 19:45.768
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:45.768 --> 19:47.645
<i>- I've got a plan</i>
<i>as far as the order</i>

19:47.645 --> 19:49.563
I'm gonna try
and do everything.

19:49.563 --> 19:54.443
I want to take care of the
issues they saw in my blade.

19:54.443 --> 19:56.320
I've got to make sure
my edge geometry is right,

19:56.320 --> 19:59.073
<i>because if I have</i>
<i>too thin of an edge,</i>

19:59.073 --> 20:01.575
it's going to crack
on that nut.

20:01.575 --> 20:06.330
And then I'd like to get
my handle constructed.

20:06.330 --> 20:09.083
Then I'm gonna focus
on the foundry and hopefully

20:09.083 --> 20:12.086
leave myself enough time
to run through the problems

20:12.086 --> 20:13.546
that I may encounter.

20:13.546 --> 20:15.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:15.715 --> 20:17.258
<i>- The fact that</i>
<i>I left my blade thick</i>

20:17.258 --> 20:18.759
and have a lot
of stock removal to do

20:18.759 --> 20:20.428
is probably gonna
bite me in the ass.

20:20.428 --> 20:22.304
- Of all of our smiths,
he had the most

20:22.304 --> 20:24.265
sacrificial material
on that thing.

20:24.265 --> 20:26.225
- Yeah, Chuck's was
really thick in the spine.

20:26.225 --> 20:28.144
<i>- And in this process</i>
<i>I'm going with,</i>

20:28.144 --> 20:29.770
<i>it's a lot</i>
<i>of trial and error,</i>

20:29.770 --> 20:31.647
a lot of fitting up,
a lot of grinding.

20:31.647 --> 20:33.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:33.065 --> 20:34.817
Clock's just ticking by.

20:34.817 --> 20:36.777
<i>I still got to cast</i>
<i>that bronze pommel.</i>

20:36.777 --> 20:38.028
Starting to get nervous.

20:38.028 --> 20:40.364
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:40.364 --> 20:42.575
<i>- I worked on</i>
<i>the warp of my tang,</i>

20:42.575 --> 20:45.870
and blade is straight
from the tip to the back.

20:45.870 --> 20:47.830
- Do you see Bill's tang
from here, man?

20:47.830 --> 20:49.874
- Tiny.
Second strength test

20:49.874 --> 20:51.959
is gonna be point down
in sheet steel,

20:51.959 --> 20:53.419
hitting that pommel,
and all that's

20:53.419 --> 20:55.212
traveling down the tang.

20:55.212 --> 20:58.215
So we might end up
with handles that go like this.

20:58.215 --> 21:00.634
- The handle material
that I choose to use is--

21:00.634 --> 21:02.303
<i>I believe they call it</i>
<i>diamondwood.</i>

21:02.303 --> 21:04.722
<i>It's a birch-laminated-type</i>
<i>handle.</i>

21:04.722 --> 21:07.725
<i>They're colorful,</i>
<i>and they seem to be strong.</i>

21:07.725 --> 21:11.562
I got to allow myself
enough time for that foundry.

21:11.562 --> 21:14.690
If I run into any problems
with this casting, it's over.

21:14.690 --> 21:16.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:16.692 --> 21:18.569
- So let's talk a little bit
about this foundry.

21:18.569 --> 21:20.070
How does it work?

21:20.070 --> 21:21.447
- Fill your crucible
full of bronze.

21:21.447 --> 21:22.865
Get it in your foundry.

21:22.865 --> 21:24.116
Light the foundry.
Melt that down.

21:24.116 --> 21:26.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:26.118 --> 21:28.621
- While my foundry
is warming up,

21:28.621 --> 21:32.041
<i>I cut a big piece of foam</i>
<i>that is enough</i>

21:32.041 --> 21:35.503
<i>for six or seven pommels,</i>
<i>'cause I have a feeling</i>

21:35.503 --> 21:38.297
it might not cast
exactly how I want it to.

21:38.297 --> 21:42.635
- What you want to do is make a
positive shape out of the foam.

21:42.635 --> 21:45.846
As in, whatever shape
you want to cast in bronze.

21:45.846 --> 21:47.181
- And then you just pour
what's in the crucible

21:47.181 --> 21:48.849
right into the top
of the flask.

21:48.849 --> 21:50.768
- Then you can grind
your shape out of that.

21:50.768 --> 21:53.062
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

21:53.062 --> 21:54.313
All right, we got
our first pour happening.

21:54.313 --> 21:55.439
- Here we go.

21:55.439 --> 21:59.151
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:59.151 --> 22:01.445
Ooh, look at that.
Cool.

22:01.445 --> 22:02.863
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:02.863 --> 22:04.323
- Well, that
didn't work at all.

22:04.323 --> 22:06.075
It didn't melt
through the foam.

22:06.075 --> 22:08.494
It kind of just made
a big glob.

22:08.494 --> 22:11.372
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:11.372 --> 22:13.165
- It looks like a cat turd.

22:13.165 --> 22:14.834
So it's got to be
packed in there.

22:14.834 --> 22:17.002
- Oh, yeah, you want
that sand packed tightly,

22:17.002 --> 22:18.838
'cause there's a lot
of things that can go wrong

22:18.838 --> 22:20.589
that you're not gonna see.
- Okay, I got you. I got you.

22:20.589 --> 22:22.716
- I'm still confident
that I have enough thick areas

22:22.716 --> 22:23.926
that I can make a pommel.

22:23.926 --> 22:26.262
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:26.262 --> 22:28.931
- It's time to get
the furnace fired up.

22:28.931 --> 22:30.850
<i>My plan is just</i>
<i>to grab this sand</i>

22:30.850 --> 22:32.643
that's already in the bucket,
go ahead and tamp it down,

22:32.643 --> 22:34.061
pack it good.

22:34.061 --> 22:35.938
- Your sand
is a casting sand.

22:35.938 --> 22:38.190
It has a certain amount of oil
in it, keeps it very wet.

22:38.190 --> 22:40.025
It's easy to pack.
<i>- Next, I'm just getting</i>

22:40.025 --> 22:42.027
a piece
of 3/4 inch pipe,

22:42.027 --> 22:44.738
<i>run the pipe down inside</i>
<i>the sand about an inch deep,</i>

22:44.738 --> 22:46.156
<i>and it's gonna give me</i>
<i>the void I need</i>

22:46.156 --> 22:48.284
<i>to pour the bronze into.</i>

22:48.284 --> 22:51.412
- When I look at Chuck, I see
a guy that's kind of no BS.

22:51.412 --> 22:53.455
Like, "I don't need this.
I don't need that."

22:53.455 --> 22:54.999
- Simple MacGyver style.

22:54.999 --> 22:56.458
- It's basically
redneck engineering

22:56.458 --> 22:57.710
whatever's laying around.

22:57.710 --> 23:00.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:00.462 --> 23:01.547
- Second pour.

23:01.547 --> 23:05.092
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:05.092 --> 23:06.886
- That was just a little,
teeny tiny bit.

23:06.886 --> 23:08.304
<i>- It's looking pretty good,</i>

23:08.304 --> 23:09.972
but I still have
a lot of work to do.

23:09.972 --> 23:13.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:13.100 --> 23:14.977
<i>- I'm cutting</i>
<i>a piece of foam out</i>

23:14.977 --> 23:17.146
<i>approximately</i>
<i>the same size as my handle.</i>

23:17.146 --> 23:20.107
- He's got one side
of the flask completely full,

23:20.107 --> 23:23.235
and now he's fully packing
the other side.

23:23.235 --> 23:25.446
Could be better to keep it
half and half in the center.

23:28.574 --> 23:31.076
And Bill's ready to pour.

23:31.076 --> 23:33.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:33.495 --> 23:34.663
- Ooh.
- Uh-oh.

23:34.663 --> 23:36.415
- Ooh.
- Oh, collapse.

23:36.415 --> 23:38.709
Oh, the whole thing
just split open.

23:38.709 --> 23:41.462
- Aw, jeezle Pete.
What am I gonna do now?

23:41.462 --> 23:44.089
- Looked like Bill
had one half of that flask...

23:44.089 --> 23:45.633
- Yeah, you're right.
- Packed sand in,

23:45.633 --> 23:47.509
put all the foam in one side,

23:47.509 --> 23:50.012
so his wall on his one side
was really thin.

23:50.012 --> 23:51.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:51.847 --> 23:54.350
<i>- Oh, wait a minute.</i>
<i>Hey, this isn't too bad.</i>

23:54.350 --> 23:56.143
- Bill doesn't seem concerned
about anything.

23:56.143 --> 23:58.687
- Well, it looks like he's got
a tiny scrap of bronze

23:58.687 --> 24:01.231
that spilled and cooled
on the table--clever.

24:01.231 --> 24:04.193
- That puddle's
about the shape of a pommel,

24:04.193 --> 24:06.195
and it's thick enough,
it'll mechanically

24:06.195 --> 24:08.614
be strong enough for a thread.

24:08.614 --> 24:11.867
That's my pommel.
I'm done with the casting.

24:11.867 --> 24:13.160
It was a great mistake.

24:13.160 --> 24:15.996
[laughs]

24:15.996 --> 24:17.623
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:17.623 --> 24:20.668
<i>- I've got my</i>
<i>funky-looking cast</i>

24:20.668 --> 24:23.587
cut out into the shape I want.

24:23.587 --> 24:27.883
<i>I get my pommel threaded</i>
<i>and screw that thing on,</i>

24:27.883 --> 24:30.010
and now I can start
shaping everything

24:30.010 --> 24:31.929
<i>and truing it all up.</i>

24:31.929 --> 24:34.682
I think about whether or not
I should address the issue

24:34.682 --> 24:36.392
that J. brought up
about my tang.

24:36.392 --> 24:38.727
<i>But my handle</i>
<i>is such a tight fit.</i>

24:38.727 --> 24:41.355
In my mind,
I think that that is going to

24:41.355 --> 24:43.357
help support my tang.

24:43.357 --> 24:46.110
- That tang looks spindly.

24:46.110 --> 24:47.987
- Thick, wide blade.
Small tang.

24:47.987 --> 24:49.655
We've seen it before.
It breaks.

24:49.655 --> 24:51.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:51.991 --> 24:53.492
<i>- Well, I got</i>
<i>my handle together.</i>

24:53.492 --> 24:55.285
It's not the prettiest thing
in the world.

24:55.285 --> 24:58.414
- How does it look?
- Blocky.

24:58.414 --> 25:00.833
- And I'm thinking, "This is
the worst knife I ever made."

25:00.833 --> 25:03.794
Even when I was starting off,
I never did that bad, you know?

25:03.794 --> 25:05.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:05.671 --> 25:07.464
- 15 minutes, bladesmiths!

25:07.464 --> 25:09.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:09.341 --> 25:11.385
- I get done with the pommel
on the belt sander.

25:11.385 --> 25:12.928
It's looking pretty good.

25:12.928 --> 25:14.972
I've got all the rough edges
off of it.

25:14.972 --> 25:16.974
Tapping and threading
this pommel

25:16.974 --> 25:20.811
<i>and this hidden tang</i>
<i>is taking all the time up.</i>

25:20.811 --> 25:23.188
So I actually throw
some epoxy in the threads,

25:23.188 --> 25:25.649
<i>thread it down by hand,</i>
<i>tie it as good as I can.</i>

25:25.649 --> 25:27.443
<i>My heart's racing</i>
<i>through my chest.</i>

25:27.443 --> 25:29.194
Wonder if I'm gonna finish
or not.

25:29.194 --> 25:31.196
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:31.196 --> 25:36.076
- 10, 9, 8, 7, 6,

25:36.076 --> 25:41.165
5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

25:41.165 --> 25:42.499
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

25:42.499 --> 25:43.625
Drop your tools.

25:43.625 --> 25:45.669
This round is over.

25:45.669 --> 25:47.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:47.171 --> 25:49.256
- Challenge two was hell.

25:49.256 --> 25:51.675
<i>I'm pretty pleased</i>
<i>that I finished the blade.</i>

25:51.675 --> 25:54.386
<i>It looks nowhere near</i>
<i>like I would want it to look.</i>

25:54.386 --> 25:56.513
It's all up to the judges now.

25:56.513 --> 26:00.642
- Bladesmiths, welcome to our
first-ever dual strength test.

26:00.642 --> 26:02.686
First, what I'm gonna do
is take your weapons,

26:02.686 --> 26:05.981
and I'm gonna put the edges
on those big industrial nuts

26:05.981 --> 26:08.609
and whale down on them
with a baton.

26:08.609 --> 26:10.736
Then I'm gonna
take the tips,

26:10.736 --> 26:12.362
put them on that sheet steel,

26:12.362 --> 26:13.697
and I'm gonna
baton those pommels

26:13.697 --> 26:15.407
that you threaded
onto your weapons,

26:15.407 --> 26:16.658
see how well they hold up.

26:16.658 --> 26:17.701
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

26:17.701 --> 26:19.828
Bill, you ready?

26:19.828 --> 26:21.121
- Yes, sir.

26:21.121 --> 26:24.041
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:24.041 --> 26:26.293
<i>I hope my blade</i>
<i>stays in one piece,</i>

26:26.293 --> 26:28.587
<i>especially when he's</i>
<i>striking it on that nut.</i>

26:28.587 --> 26:31.090
<i>And this is all</i>
<i>building up the anxiety.</i>

26:31.090 --> 26:32.216
You know, come on.

26:32.216 --> 26:35.385
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.385 --> 26:38.347
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:38.347 --> 26:41.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:41.934 --> 26:43.852
[Bleep].
[chuckles]

26:43.852 --> 26:46.897
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:46.897 --> 26:48.857
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:48.857 --> 26:51.860
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:51.860 --> 26:57.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:57.407 --> 26:59.952
- Good job, man.

26:59.952 --> 27:01.245
Good job.

27:01.245 --> 27:04.790
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:04.790 --> 27:06.416
- All right, Bill,
we got a couple issues here.

27:06.416 --> 27:08.252
Overall, your handle
held up well.

27:08.252 --> 27:10.879
Your threaded pommel
held up to that batoning.

27:10.879 --> 27:14.550
Big issue is your blade.
We're missing some pieces here.

27:14.550 --> 27:17.052
First blow on that nut,
it just rounded off a bit.

27:17.052 --> 27:19.847
The second two actually
took bites out of it.

27:19.847 --> 27:21.807
And when we did
the sheet steel,

27:21.807 --> 27:23.892
your tip came off as well.

27:23.892 --> 27:25.519
You can actually
still see it in there.

27:25.519 --> 27:27.437
So it's a bit
on the brittle side.

27:27.437 --> 27:31.066
But overall, it's light.
It feels good in the hand.

27:31.066 --> 27:33.652
So...nicely done.
- Thank you.

27:33.652 --> 27:36.905
- Chuck, how you feeling?
- Not too good.

27:36.905 --> 27:38.282
- We're gonna do it anyhow.
- Let's do it.

27:38.282 --> 27:39.992
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:39.992 --> 27:42.202
<i>- After I see Bill's</i>
<i>edge deformation</i>

27:42.202 --> 27:45.247
<i>and his tip breaking off,</i>
<i>my heart's racing.</i>

27:45.247 --> 27:47.749
<i>If this guy's work's gonna</i>
<i>suffer this kind of damage,</i>

27:47.749 --> 27:48.917
what's mine gonna do?

27:48.917 --> 27:51.795
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:51.795 --> 27:54.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:54.673 --> 27:57.593
<i>[rock music]</i>

27:57.593 --> 28:04.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:06.143 --> 28:08.061
- Jesus Pete.

28:08.061 --> 28:09.938
<i>- All I can figure</i>
<i>is something</i>

28:09.938 --> 28:11.315
<i>in the grain structure</i>
<i>of the metal</i>

28:11.315 --> 28:12.983
in that certain area
didn't hold up.

28:12.983 --> 28:15.319
<i>A catastrophic failure</i>
<i>happened.</i>

28:15.319 --> 28:17.029
This is a hell of a test.

28:17.029 --> 28:18.864
- Chuck,
your blade has suffered

28:18.864 --> 28:20.324
a catastrophic failure,

28:20.324 --> 28:22.826
only making it
to the third strike.

28:22.826 --> 28:25.078
However, you're not done yet.

28:25.078 --> 28:27.664
It would seem that
both you and Cole's fate

28:27.664 --> 28:30.292
lie with the strength
of Cole's blade.

28:30.292 --> 28:33.587
Now, Cole, your blade still has
to survive the strength test.

28:33.587 --> 28:36.632
It's got to make it through at
least three licks on that nut.

28:36.632 --> 28:38.175
Do you think you got
what it takes?

28:38.175 --> 28:40.719
- Well, let's see what happens.
- All right.

28:40.719 --> 28:43.847
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:43.847 --> 28:46.642
<i>- I'm definitely nervous</i>
<i>about how it's gonna hold up.</i>

28:46.642 --> 28:50.687
<i>J. has a reputation</i>
<i>of beating the [bleep]</i>

28:50.687 --> 28:52.731
<i>out of all</i>
<i>the knives he tests,</i>

28:52.731 --> 28:56.276
and, you know, I'm expecting
him to not hold back on mine.

28:56.276 --> 28:59.237
<i>I'm worried about that</i>
<i>weak part of my spine.</i>

28:59.237 --> 29:02.157
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

29:02.157 --> 29:09.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:13.627 --> 29:15.587
<i>- Chuck's blade broke</i>
<i>on the third strike,</i>

29:15.587 --> 29:18.215
so I know that
I have to get through

29:18.215 --> 29:20.509
the baton test to be safe.

29:20.509 --> 29:21.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.677 --> 29:22.886
I'm definitely nervous.

29:22.886 --> 29:25.847
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:25.847 --> 29:27.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:27.891 --> 29:30.811
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

29:30.811 --> 29:37.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:43.073 --> 29:45.075
[grunts]

29:45.075 --> 29:46.827
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:46.827 --> 29:48.537
- Chuck, Cole,
we find ourselves

29:48.537 --> 29:51.164
in interesting circumstances.

29:51.164 --> 29:53.041
Both of your blades
suffered catastrophic failures

29:53.041 --> 29:54.793
in the middle
of our strength test.

29:54.793 --> 29:58.255
However, Chuck, your blade
survived three strikes,

29:58.255 --> 30:01.049
and, Cole, your blade
only went for two.

30:01.049 --> 30:02.843
So with that in mind,
I have to ask you,

30:02.843 --> 30:04.928
Cole, please leave The Forge.

30:04.928 --> 30:06.930
<i>- That was pretty close.</i>

30:06.930 --> 30:09.016
I really thought I was
gonna make it through.

30:09.016 --> 30:10.434
<i>Proud of what I made.</i>

30:10.434 --> 30:13.270
It broke,
but I think it looked great.

30:13.270 --> 30:17.232
I'm still a bladesmith, and I'm
gonna keep on keeping on.

30:17.232 --> 30:19.192
- I'm happy to be
moving forward.

30:19.192 --> 30:21.445
I would have liked it to be
under better circumstances.

30:21.445 --> 30:23.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:23.113 --> 30:24.990
- Bill, Chuck, congratulations.

30:24.990 --> 30:27.200
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

30:27.200 --> 30:28.827
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

30:28.827 --> 30:31.788
to re-create an iconic
weapon from history.

30:31.788 --> 30:32.873
That weapon is...

30:32.873 --> 30:34.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:34.916 --> 30:37.586
The Celtic
anthropomorphic sword.

30:37.586 --> 30:40.881
- Mm.
- [coughs]

30:40.881 --> 30:43.467
<i>- The Celtic anthropomorphic</i>
<i>sword is an Iron Age weapon</i>

30:43.467 --> 30:45.594
<i>that's both elegant</i>
<i>and lethal.</i>

30:45.594 --> 30:48.138
<i>It boasts a distinctive hilt</i>
<i>displaying anthropomorphic,</i>

30:48.138 --> 30:51.600
<i>meaning humanlike, features,</i>
<i>often cast from bronze.</i>

30:51.600 --> 30:54.144
<i>A fearsome killer, the sword's</i>
<i>strong double-edged point</i>

30:54.144 --> 30:55.937
<i>could be used</i>
<i>as a deadly thruster</i>

30:55.937 --> 30:57.939
<i>as well as a swift slasher,</i>

30:57.939 --> 31:01.068
<i>capable of quick attacks</i>
<i>in close-quarters combat.</i>

31:01.068 --> 31:03.737
<i>A classic of Iron Age</i>
<i>Celtic weaponry,</i>

31:03.737 --> 31:06.198
<i>the sword battles on</i>
<i>in popular culture,</i>

31:06.198 --> 31:10.702
<i>including the 2011</i>
<i>historical drama "The Eagle."</i>

31:10.702 --> 31:12.537
The blades themselves
must fall within

31:12.537 --> 31:14.039
the following parameters.

31:14.039 --> 31:15.707
The length of your
double-edged blade

31:15.707 --> 31:18.835
must fall
between 22 and 23 inches

31:18.835 --> 31:21.713
and be light enough to be
wielded with a single hand.

31:21.713 --> 31:24.800
You must also cast from bronze
a pommel and guard

31:24.800 --> 31:26.760
in the anthropomorphic style.

31:26.760 --> 31:29.346
- Anthropomorphic sword.

31:29.346 --> 31:31.348
<i>It's the first time</i>
<i>I ever heard of one.</i>

31:31.348 --> 31:32.974
It looks like it's gonna be
a real pain in the ass.

31:32.974 --> 31:34.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:34.643 --> 31:36.478
- At the end of five days,
you will return

31:36.478 --> 31:38.313
to present your swords
to our panel of expert judges,

31:38.313 --> 31:40.315
and only after they've
thoroughly inspected

31:40.315 --> 31:43.151
and brutally tested your blades
will they declare one of you

31:43.151 --> 31:45.237
the "Forged in Fire" champion
who also walks away

31:45.237 --> 31:46.780
with that check for 10 grand.

31:46.780 --> 31:47.864
Good luck, bladesmiths.

31:47.864 --> 31:49.116
We'll see you in five days.

31:49.116 --> 31:49.991
- Good luck.
- You too.

31:49.991 --> 31:51.785
- Thank you.

31:51.785 --> 31:55.163
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

31:55.163 --> 31:57.791
- It's day one. I'm back
in my home shop in Kingsley.

31:57.791 --> 32:02.587
I'm really anxious to start
the anthropomorphic sword.

32:02.587 --> 32:04.256
<i>The biggest challenge</i>
<i>is gonna be</i>

32:04.256 --> 32:06.091
the casting
of the handle parts.

32:06.091 --> 32:08.301
These are the best.
It looks like I'm scuba diving,

32:08.301 --> 32:10.178
but it doesn't
fog your glasses up.

32:10.178 --> 32:14.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:14.182 --> 32:15.851
<i>The first thing</i>
<i>I got to do today</i>

32:15.851 --> 32:18.311
<i>is get my steel cut</i>
<i>for the Damascus.</i>

32:18.311 --> 32:20.480
<i>I want to try</i>
<i>for a high layer count,</i>

32:20.480 --> 32:22.858
<i>something that makes the steel</i>
<i>look shimmery in the light.</i>

32:22.858 --> 32:24.442
I want to make this blade
really pretty.

32:24.442 --> 32:25.777
Now we'll get it hot.

32:25.777 --> 32:27.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:27.779 --> 32:29.114
That's a big billet.

32:29.114 --> 32:33.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:33.493 --> 32:35.370
All good welds.

32:35.370 --> 32:37.622
Going to fold it over
about seven times.

32:37.622 --> 32:40.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.500 --> 32:42.460
<i>Tomorrow I plan on putting</i>
<i>the pattern in it,</i>

32:42.460 --> 32:45.380
getting the bevels on it,
probably putting a tang on it.

32:45.380 --> 32:47.174
<i>Right now, I'm feeling good</i>
<i>about my billet,</i>

32:47.174 --> 32:49.050
but I've had
enough work for today.

32:49.050 --> 32:51.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:51.970 --> 32:53.555
<i>- It's great to be back</i>
<i>at my own home forge.</i>

32:53.555 --> 32:55.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:55.390 --> 32:58.059
This sword is pretty complex
and complicated.

32:58.059 --> 32:59.936
I've never done one
this style before.

32:59.936 --> 33:01.062
I hope I can pull it off.

33:01.062 --> 33:02.981
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:02.981 --> 33:04.399
<i>Today I'm gonna get</i>
<i>all my metals together,</i>

33:04.399 --> 33:06.443
<i>start getting stuff cut up.</i>

33:06.443 --> 33:08.361
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:08.361 --> 33:11.281
I want to build that sword
out of Damascus steel.

33:11.281 --> 33:13.366
<i>I think it'll</i>
<i>give it more character.</i>

33:13.366 --> 33:15.702
I'm gonna have to get
each billet welded up

33:15.702 --> 33:18.079
and then incorporate
both those billets together

33:18.079 --> 33:21.333
in order to get enough length
and width to make the sword.

33:21.333 --> 33:23.210
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:23.210 --> 33:26.171
I wanted to do the full
23 inches out of Damascus.

33:26.171 --> 33:29.466
I see today, after five hours,
how time-consuming it is.

33:29.466 --> 33:32.469
<i>I could just go fully</i>
<i>with a 1095 bar</i>

33:32.469 --> 33:34.429
<i>and build the sword</i>
<i>from there.</i>

33:34.429 --> 33:35.597
We'll see how it goes tomorrow.

33:35.597 --> 33:38.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:38.016 --> 33:39.517
<i>- Well, it's the start</i>
<i>of day three.</i>

33:39.517 --> 33:41.102
<i>We're running out of time.</i>

33:41.102 --> 33:43.730
<i>I need to get</i>
<i>the castings done.</i>

33:43.730 --> 33:45.523
I haven't really done
any bronze casting

33:45.523 --> 33:47.317
except for the second round,

33:47.317 --> 33:49.152
<i>and it didn't</i>
<i>come out real well.</i>

33:49.152 --> 33:51.238
I think I can do better.

33:51.238 --> 33:53.073
<i>I'm going to use some</i>
<i>green foam from the florist</i>

33:53.073 --> 33:56.284
<i>and carve my patterns</i>
<i>and pour it.</i>

33:56.284 --> 33:59.287
I got Gumby for the pommel.

33:59.287 --> 34:01.373
Hopefully, this works out.

34:01.373 --> 34:03.416
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:03.416 --> 34:04.876
This has got to work,
or I don't know

34:04.876 --> 34:06.044
what I'm gonna do.

34:06.044 --> 34:09.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:09.881 --> 34:12.968
It didn't work.
It just stopped at the foam.

34:12.968 --> 34:15.387
<i>Maybe I didn't</i>
<i>pack the sand tight enough.</i>

34:15.387 --> 34:16.888
I got an idea.

34:16.888 --> 34:18.139
The only thing I can think of

34:18.139 --> 34:20.141
is making, like,
a cookie pattern.

34:20.141 --> 34:23.144
<i>I plan to make the outline</i>
<i>of the object in wood,</i>

34:23.144 --> 34:26.273
press it in the sand,
and set the mold up to pour

34:26.273 --> 34:27.649
with the impression in it.

34:27.649 --> 34:30.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.068 --> 34:32.612
I can't give up on this,
because if I do,

34:32.612 --> 34:34.739
I'm out of this money.

34:34.739 --> 34:36.866
Success.

34:36.866 --> 34:39.577
It's kind of ugly,
but I can work with ugly.

34:39.577 --> 34:41.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:41.705 --> 34:44.457
<i>- Day four, I feel like</i>
<i>I'm a little bit behind.</i>

34:44.457 --> 34:46.334
<i>I ended up</i>
<i>having to shift gears,</i>

34:46.334 --> 34:48.753
<i>going away</i>
<i>from my Damascus billets.</i>

34:48.753 --> 34:51.589
<i>So I grabbed</i>
<i>a big chunk of 4041,</i>

34:51.589 --> 34:53.466
<i>got the blade</i>
<i>completely forged.</i>

34:53.466 --> 34:55.844
I'm gonna cast
this bronze handle today.

34:55.844 --> 34:57.554
<i>If I have enough time,</i>
<i>I'm gonna try</i>

34:57.554 --> 35:00.307
<i>and pull some of the weight</i>
<i>off the sword.</i>

35:00.307 --> 35:02.100
All right,
let's get it fired up.

35:02.100 --> 35:05.270
I've decided to cast
directly onto my tang.

35:05.270 --> 35:07.230
<i>It's gonna save time.</i>

35:07.230 --> 35:09.566
<i>There won't be a bunch</i>
<i>of drilling and filing.</i>

35:09.566 --> 35:12.235
<i>If I can pull it off,</i>
<i>it's a one-shot deal.</i>

35:12.235 --> 35:14.446
<i>Hopefully,</i>
<i>everything goes well,</i>

35:14.446 --> 35:17.574
<i>I capture the details in the</i>
<i>handle that I want to capture.</i>

35:17.574 --> 35:18.908
It should look pretty cool.

35:18.908 --> 35:21.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:21.661 --> 35:23.413
Well, some of the casting
was lost.

35:23.413 --> 35:24.998
I don't know what happened,

35:24.998 --> 35:27.125
but it didn't take
all the way.

35:27.125 --> 35:29.085
<i>This ain't the kind of work</i>
<i>I [bleep] do.</i>

35:29.085 --> 35:31.046
It has severe voids in it.

35:31.046 --> 35:34.007
<i>I'm gonna have</i>
<i>to cut it off the tang.</i>

35:34.007 --> 35:35.759
<i>I'm gonna think</i>
<i>about it tonight,</i>

35:35.759 --> 35:37.135
see if I can figure out
what went wrong.

35:37.135 --> 35:39.471
Tomorrow's the last day.

35:39.471 --> 35:41.389
I'm gonna give it another try
first thing in the morning,

35:41.389 --> 35:43.516
see what happens.

35:43.516 --> 35:45.769
<i>- Today's day four.</i>

35:45.769 --> 35:48.271
There's light at the end
of the tunnel.

35:48.271 --> 35:51.149
First thing I got to do today
is thread the tang.

35:51.149 --> 35:53.234
<i>I'm gonna take my time</i>
<i>doing this,</i>

35:53.234 --> 35:54.903
<i>make sure it's done right,</i>
<i>because I know there's gonna</i>

35:54.903 --> 35:57.155
be a lot of force
on this handle.

35:57.155 --> 36:01.534
This is an anthropomorphic
handle, undressed.

36:01.534 --> 36:03.328
There's nothing in between.

36:03.328 --> 36:06.623
You know,
he got no clothes on.

36:06.623 --> 36:08.458
<i>I put an African blackwood</i>
<i>handle onto it,</i>

36:08.458 --> 36:10.418
<i>so I hope it kind of</i>
<i>matches the darkness</i>

36:10.418 --> 36:12.712
that's in the Damascus.

36:12.712 --> 36:14.130
<i>Now I got</i>
<i>to grind my blade</i>

36:14.130 --> 36:15.840
to get a nice
sharp edge on it

36:15.840 --> 36:17.717
<i>and make it look</i>
<i>as good as I can.</i>

36:17.717 --> 36:19.386
I know that it'll cut.

36:19.386 --> 36:22.389
I got two Band-Aids
to prove it right here.

36:22.389 --> 36:23.473
<i>[laughs]</i>

36:23.473 --> 36:25.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:25.392 --> 36:27.852
- Day five.
Time is running out.

36:27.852 --> 36:30.897
I've got to cast this
bronze handle one more time.

36:30.897 --> 36:33.566
After that, I need to get
some of the weight off of it.

36:33.566 --> 36:35.235
Shouldn't be a big issue,

36:35.235 --> 36:37.529
<i>as long as I get</i>
<i>this handle in place.</i>

36:37.529 --> 36:39.864
I am gonna try it
vertical this time.

36:39.864 --> 36:42.575
I'm gonna finish filling
this up, tamp it down.

36:42.575 --> 36:45.161
If it don't work this time,
that's it.

36:45.161 --> 36:48.373
<i>In theory, I could actually</i>
<i>bury the handle deep enough</i>

36:48.373 --> 36:50.417
to where the molten bronze
would go down

36:50.417 --> 36:54.170
and have nowhere to escape
and go around the tang.

36:54.170 --> 36:57.048
I just don't have enough time
to cast another bronze handle.

36:57.048 --> 36:58.745
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:02.429 --> 37:05.014
- [bleep], wasn't enough.

37:05.014 --> 37:08.268
My second attempt at casting
is a bust.

37:08.268 --> 37:11.855
I'm [bleep] done. I am done.
I--no more.

37:11.855 --> 37:13.356
I'm ready to just quit.
I'm not gonna

37:13.356 --> 37:15.400
complete this sword at all.

37:15.400 --> 37:17.569
<i>But then</i>
<i>I got to think about Bill.</i>

37:17.569 --> 37:20.655
It wouldn't be fair to him.
So I continue on.

37:20.655 --> 37:22.449
<i>I want to get</i>
<i>a completed sword up there,</i>

37:22.449 --> 37:24.159
<i>so I'm just</i>
<i>gonna do it my way,</i>

37:24.159 --> 37:26.077
<i>make it look as good as I can.</i>

37:26.077 --> 37:28.580
I had a lot of issues
these past five days.

37:28.580 --> 37:30.915
I pushed through,
and I'm glad I got it done.

37:30.915 --> 37:34.002
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:34.002 --> 37:36.129
- Bill, Chuck,
welcome back to The Forge.

37:36.129 --> 37:38.465
Each of you has had
five days at your home forges

37:38.465 --> 37:41.301
to work on your Celtic
anthropomorphic swords.

37:41.301 --> 37:42.886
Bill, how did it go for you?

37:42.886 --> 37:44.095
- Blade went great.

37:44.095 --> 37:46.055
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

37:46.055 --> 37:50.393
<i>The blade is a Damascus</i>
<i>with approximately 270 layers.</i>

37:50.393 --> 37:51.811
<i>Brass-cast handle.</i>

37:51.811 --> 37:53.605
<i>I put a rosebud pattern in it</i>

37:53.605 --> 37:55.565
<i>that gives a nice appearance.</i>

37:55.565 --> 37:57.650
- All right.
Chuck, how do you feel?

37:57.650 --> 37:59.194
- Uh, I was all over the board.

37:59.194 --> 38:00.862
The bronze casting
was a real pain.

38:00.862 --> 38:02.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:02.906 --> 38:06.075
<i>The blade construction</i>
<i>is 1095 bar.</i>

38:06.075 --> 38:08.828
<i>It was a large chunk, got it</i>
<i>down to where I needed it to.</i>

38:08.828 --> 38:11.289
<i>The handle is my style.</i>

38:11.289 --> 38:14.250
- All right, bladesmiths,
you know what's next.

38:14.250 --> 38:16.127
It's time to see
how they hold up in our tests.

38:16.127 --> 38:17.378
There will be three:

38:17.378 --> 38:19.714
a strength test,
a sharpness test,

38:19.714 --> 38:22.926
and, up first, the kill test.
Doug?

38:22.926 --> 38:24.844
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:24.844 --> 38:28.139
- Bladesmiths,
this is the kill test.

38:28.139 --> 38:30.558
To see what kind of lethal
damage your sword will do,

38:30.558 --> 38:32.268
I will take your weapon
and deliver killing blows

38:32.268 --> 38:34.020
on this ram carcass.

38:34.020 --> 38:36.314
Bill, ready for the kill?

38:36.314 --> 38:37.941
- Yes, I am.

38:37.941 --> 38:39.651
The ram, I think,
is really appropriate

38:39.651 --> 38:42.695
for the period of the weapon
that we reproduced.

38:42.695 --> 38:45.824
But it's got hair on it, and
that hair's pretty abrasive.

38:45.824 --> 38:47.867
<i>And that's the only thing</i>
<i>I'm worried about--</i>

38:47.867 --> 38:51.412
my sword cutting that hair
to get to the flesh.

38:51.412 --> 38:52.997
[exhales sharply]

38:52.997 --> 38:58.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:58.169 --> 39:00.129
- [exhales]

39:00.129 --> 39:04.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:04.175 --> 39:06.177
- Man.

39:06.177 --> 39:07.720
[exhales]

39:07.720 --> 39:09.347
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

39:09.347 --> 39:11.516
- That's one sharp sword.

39:11.516 --> 39:13.560
- All right, Bill, let's talk
about your blade right here.

39:13.560 --> 39:15.895
First up,
your handle feels good.

39:15.895 --> 39:18.523
It's got a nice shape to it,
and it just fits nicely.

39:18.523 --> 39:19.774
I like the guard.
I like the bronze

39:19.774 --> 39:21.359
that you have right there.

39:21.359 --> 39:24.028
I can immediately tell
where the edge is.

39:24.028 --> 39:27.115
This is what I don't like
about your blade.

39:27.115 --> 39:28.867
It doesn't allow me
to have fun.

39:28.867 --> 39:32.161
Two hits, it's done.
This is really light,

39:32.161 --> 39:33.955
fast, and sharp.

39:33.955 --> 39:37.166
Bill, it will kill.

39:37.166 --> 39:38.459
- Thank you. [chuckles]

39:38.459 --> 39:40.503
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

39:40.503 --> 39:41.629
- All right, Chuck,
it's your turn.

39:41.629 --> 39:42.755
You ready?
- Yes, sir.

39:42.755 --> 39:44.007
- Let's do this.

39:44.007 --> 39:46.968
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:46.968 --> 39:53.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:53.975 --> 39:55.422
All right.

39:58.104 --> 40:00.023
<i>- I'm feeling</i>
<i>a little anxious.</i>

40:00.023 --> 40:03.318
<i>I'm up next, and I see</i>
<i>all four of the judges</i>

40:03.318 --> 40:05.570
huddling up,
discussing my blade.

40:05.570 --> 40:10.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:13.244 --> 40:14.787
- Oof.

40:14.787 --> 40:16.706
That's a lot of weight, man.

40:16.706 --> 40:19.667
I completely agree.
- Single-handedly.

40:19.667 --> 40:22.670
- Yeah, okay, all right.
- We're in.

40:22.670 --> 40:25.673
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:25.673 --> 40:29.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:29.344 --> 40:31.679
- [exhales]

40:31.679 --> 40:35.642
Chuck, Doug's taken a look
at your sword,

40:35.642 --> 40:38.019
and it's just too heavy
to wield safely.

40:38.019 --> 40:40.188
The parameters specifically
called for a sword

40:40.188 --> 40:42.148
that was light enough
to wield one-handed.

40:42.148 --> 40:44.275
- Yes, sir.
- Additionally,

40:44.275 --> 40:46.486
you were to have cast a bronze

40:46.486 --> 40:48.780
anthropomorphic
guard and pommel.

40:48.780 --> 40:52.158
<i>Yours are not castings,</i>
<i>and they're not bronze.</i>

40:52.158 --> 40:56.537
Chuck, because your blade
failed to meet the parameters,

40:56.537 --> 40:59.624
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

40:59.624 --> 41:01.918
<i>- Oh, I agree</i>
<i>with the judges 100%.</i>

41:01.918 --> 41:04.337
My blade's too heavy.
There's no doubt about it.

41:04.337 --> 41:06.297
Congratulations, Bill.
- Thank you.

41:06.297 --> 41:08.591
<i>- Mine looks like something</i>
<i>off a sci-fi fantasy show,</i>

41:08.591 --> 41:10.718
<i>and Bill's blade</i>
<i>looks excellent.</i>

41:10.718 --> 41:12.387
<i>I'm still a winner,</i>
<i>'cause I'm walking out</i>

41:12.387 --> 41:14.722
with the friendship of Bill
and bladesmithing.

41:14.722 --> 41:16.349
<i>In the end, that's all</i>
<i>that matters anyway.</i>

41:16.349 --> 41:19.185
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:19.185 --> 41:22.480
- Well, Bill, you are now our
new "Forged in Fire" champion.

41:22.480 --> 41:25.024
It's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:25.024 --> 41:27.860
- Thanks--thanks very much.
Words can't describe.

41:27.860 --> 41:29.320
- Why don't you come over here
and shake our hands?

41:29.320 --> 41:31.072
Good job, brother.
- Oh, thank you.

41:31.072 --> 41:33.741
I'm 71 years old, and I guess
I kicked butt today.

41:33.741 --> 41:35.326
- Beautiful job, Bill.
- Thank you.

41:35.326 --> 41:36.828
<i>Money is a great thing</i>
<i>to think about,</i>

41:36.828 --> 41:39.747
but it's the title.
I'm tickled.

41:39.747 --> 41:41.833
I'm tickled to death.

41:41.833 --> 41:43.918
I'm the "Forged in Fire"
champion, whoo!

41:43.918 --> 41:45.044
[laughs]

41:45.044 --> 41:47.964
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

41:47.964 --> 41:51.759
<i>♪ ♪</i>
